        "name": "Validation experiments performed on the same FDA generic pump geometry at COU operating conditions",
        "description": "Validation must use the FDA generic centrifugal pump geometry operated within the COU flow-speed envelope; surrogate geometries or extrapolated operating points are not acceptable."
      },
      "rationale": "All validation experiments used the FDA-defined generic centrifugal pump geometry at the five COU operating points. No surrogate geometries were used. Validation activities are directly relevant to the COU. Level 4 achieved."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cou2/numerical-solver-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error as a distinct ASME V&V 40 factor addresses iterative convergence and floating-point round-off separate from discretization error. In this V&V 40 assessment, iterative convergence is fully subsumed within the Discretization Error factor (GCI study), which accounts for all numerical approximation errors including solver residual contributions. The assessment team determined that isolating a separate numerical solver error factor would be redundant and would not provide additional credibility information beyond what the GCI analysis already captures. This factor is therefore not-applicable to the current COU2 assessment scope."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cou2/use-error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Use error in ASME V&V 40 refers to errors arising from incorrect application of the simulation tool by the analyst (e.g., incorrect boundary condition specification, misapplication of turbulence models). In this assessment, use error is addressed through the Software Quality Assurance factor, which mandates a documented simulation workflow with peer review checkpoints at each setup stage. Because the SQA process institutionally controls analyst use error through mandatory independent review of all CFD setups before execution, a separate use error factor assessment would be duplicative. This factor is not-applicable as a standalone credibility factor in this V&V 40 COU2 scope."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cou2/model-form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Model form uncertainty relates to the choice of governing equations and constitutive models (e.g., turbulence closure, hemolysis power-law model). In this COU2 assessment, model form is addressed indirectly through the Output Comparison factor: the achieved NIH predictions within 15% of experimental data provide empirical evidence that the chosen model form (k-ω SST turbulence, Giersiepen-Wurzinger hemolysis model) is adequate for the COU. A separate model form credibility factor assessment would require independent model-form uncertainty quantification beyond what the validation evidence already provides, and the assessment team has determined this is outside the contracted scope for COU2. This factor is not-applicable to the present assessment."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cou2/model-inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The Model Inputs factor in ASME V&V 40 addresses uncertainty in material properties and boundary conditions used as model inputs. For this VAD hemolysis assessment, all model inputs (blood viscosity, density, pump geometry, rotational speed, flow rate) are either precisely controlled experimental parameters or published FDA-defined geometry specifications with negligible uncertainty. The Monte Carlo UQ performed for this assessment propagates the only material input uncertainty (blood viscosity ±5%) and demonstrates that resulting NIH uncertainty is within the output comparison tolerance. A separate model inputs credibility factor is therefore not-applicable because input uncertainty is fully characterised within the existing UQ activity."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cou2/test-samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "The Test Samples factor addresses variability arising from biological or material sample-to-sample differences in physical experiments. For the FDA generic centrifugal pump hemolysis benchmark, the test article is a precisely machined metal pump with negligible unit-to-unit geometric variation; the working fluid is a standardised bovine blood analogue prepared to a controlled haematocrit (40 ± 1%). There is no meaningful sample population variability to characterise. This factor is not-applicable because the experimental setup eliminates the sample variability that this factor is designed to quantify."
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/morrison/factor/cou2/equivalency-input-parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Equivalency of input parameters addresses the degree to which the simulation input parameters match those of the physical system being represented, particularly when validation experiments use surrogate or simplified test articles. In this COU2 assessment, the validation experiments were conducted on the identical FDA generic pump geometry under the identical COU operating conditions (same flow rates, RPM, and fluid properties). There is no gap between the validation experiment inputs and the COU inputs that would require an equivalency assessment. This factor is not-applicable because the direct correspondence between experiment and COU eliminates the equivalency concern this factor is designed to address."
    }
  ],
